Sugar Prices May Drop Next Week on Lower Demand From China, Survey Shows

-- B y   A s h l e y   L u t z   a n d   I s i s   A l m e i d a
-- 
2011-05-12T23:00:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-12/sugar-prices-may-retreat-on-lower-demand-from-china-survey-says.html
Sugar may fall next week on signs
that demand is slowing in  China , the world’s largest consumer.  Eight of 12 traders, analysts and brokers surveyed by
Bloomberg News said that raw sugar traded in  New York  will fall.
Three forecast a gain, and one said prices would be little
changed. Before today, futures for July delivery gained 4.2
percent this week to 21.33 cents a pound.  Nine of 12 respondents said refined sugar on  London ’s NYSE
Liffe exchange will decline. Two said prices will rise, and one
expected little change. Through yesterday, futures gained 3.5
percent this week to $602.10 a metric ton.  Refined sugar’s premium over raw sweetener may widen next
week, according to six of 12 respondents. Three forecast little
change, and three said the spread will narrow.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Steve Stroth at 
 sstroth@bloomberg.net  